## Abstract

We present a calibrated, interpretable machine learning system for predicting
blood-brain barrier (BBB) permeability from molecular SMILES strings. The system
combines a Random Forest classifier trained on the B3DB benchmark (7,807 experimentally
validated compounds) with a multi-component decision layer integrating CNS
drug-likeness rules, structural similarity scoring, and applicability domain awareness.
The final classification formula weights calibrated ML probability (50%), CNS
physicochemical rules (35%), and structural similarity (15%), with ten chemistry-based
override rules to handle structural classes where ML probability alone is insufficient.
Benchmark validation on 15 curated molecules with known BBB status yielded 100%
correct classification. The model achieves AUC-ROC of 0.9617 and a Brier score of
0.082 on the B3DB test set, representing a 9.2% improvement over the published
DeepChem baseline.

---

## 1. Introduction

Blood-brain barrier (BBB) permeability is one of the most critical ADMET properties
in central nervous system (CNS) drug discovery. The BBB is a highly selective
semipermeable membrane formed by brain capillary endothelial cells, tight junctions,
astrocytes, and pericytes. It restricts the passage of approximately 98% of small
molecule drugs from the systemic circulation into the brain parenchyma (Pardridge,
2005). Failure to achieve adequate CNS penetration is a leading cause of attrition
in CNS development programs, making early-stage BBB prediction an important
computational filter.

Traditional BBB prediction relied on physicochemical rules derived from analysis of
known CNS drugs. Pajouhesh and Lenz (2005) established that CNS-active drugs
typically satisfy: molecular weight below 450 Da, calculated LogP between -0.5 and
5.0, topological polar surface area below 90 Å², hydrogen bond donor count of three
or fewer, hydrogen bond acceptor count of seven or fewer, and rotatable bond count
of eight or fewer. While these rules provide useful heuristics, they are insufficient
on their own because BBB transport also depends on active efflux (P-glycoprotein,
BCRP), transporter-mediated uptake (LAT1, GLUT1), and ionisation state at
physiological pH (Gabathuler, 2010).

Machine learning approaches have increasingly supplemented rule-based methods.
Classical models including random forests, support vector machines, and logistic
regression have shown strong performance on curated BBB datasets. Graph neural
networks, particularly attention-based architectures such as AttentiveFP (Xiong et al.,
2019), have demonstrated competitive results by learning directly from molecular
topology without manual feature engineering. The Blood-Brain Barrier Database (B3DB),
compiled by Meng et al. (2021) from 50 peer-reviewed experimental sources, provides a
gold-standard benchmark of 7,807 compounds for training and evaluating such models.

This report describes the development, validation, and scientific interpretation of
BBB Permeability Predictor v6.1, a multi-component decision-support system that
integrates ML probability, CNS rules, structural similarity, and applicability domain
awareness into a unified classification framework.

